{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533896"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:40:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:40:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14873"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14873"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.87,0.01,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7564"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59122"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7564"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14873"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44533"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2796"},{"type":"tags","id":"3545"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18495"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45758"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59122"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with increasing fatigue and unexplained weight loss over six weeks. She was discharged from hospital two months ago following an admission for acute coronary syndrome and atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response. Her medications were adjusted during admission, and she was started on five new medications. Her current medications are amiodarone, aspirin, bisoprolol, ramipril, and atorvastatin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 102/min and irregular, blood pressure 138/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She has a fine tremor in her outstretched hands. Thyroid function tests reveal: thyroid stimulating hormone 0.01 mU/L (0.4-4.0), free thyroxine 35 pmol/L (9-19), free triiodothyronine 12 pmol/L (3.0-7.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is responsible for the patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atorvastatin","Amiodarone","Aspirin","Ramipril","Bisoprolol"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and biochemical features of hyperthyroidism, which has developed following the initiation of several new medications. Of the medications listed, \u003Cstrong\u003Eamiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E is well-known to cause thyroid dysfunction in up to 15-20% of patients, due to its high iodine content (37% by weight) and direct toxic effects on the thyroid gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is an anti-platelet agent used in the management of acute coronary syndromes. It is not known to affect thyroid function. \u003Cstrong\u003EBisoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E is a beta-blocker commonly used in atrial fibrillation for rate control. While it can mask some symptoms of hyperthyroidism (such as palpitations and tremor), it does not cause thyroid dysfunction. \u003Cstrong\u003ERamipril\u003C/strong\u003E is an angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor used for blood pressure control and cardiac protection. It has no documented effects on thyroid function. \u003Cstrong\u003EAtorvastatin\u003C/strong\u003E is a cholesterol-lowering medication that works by inhibiting HMG-CoA reductase. It does not affect thyroid function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAmiodarone-induced thyroid dysfunction can manifest as either hypothyroidism or hyperthyroidism. Type 1 amiodarone-induced thyrotoxicosis occurs in patients with underlying thyroid disease and is caused by iodine excess, while Type 2 occurs in normal thyroid glands and is caused by destructive thyroiditis. The onset can be delayed for months after starting therapy due to amiodarone\u0027s long half-life and storage in adipose tissue. Regular monitoring of thyroid function is recommended in patients on amiodarone therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Amiodarone commonly causes thyroid dysfunction due to its high iodine content and/or direct toxic effects on the thyroid gland.","Both hypothyroidism and hyperthyroidism can occur with amiodarone therapy, necessitating regular thyroid function monitoring."],"references":["Florek JB, Girzadas D, Lucas A. Amiodarone. In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482154/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44533"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14873"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44533"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-04T22:02:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-04T22:03:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7564"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59122"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}